is a system less responsive to its citizens and more onerous\nfor development, less accountable and yet at a higher cost. ","index":"00245","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Will\nthis minister just listen to these criticisms? Will he withdraw Bill&nbsp;37\ntoday? ","index":"00246","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nJohnson:</b> The members talk a great game about listening, but they're all\ntalk and no action. ","index":"00247","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"����� We've\nlistened to stakeholders from all sides. For us, the consultation is�<i>[interjection]</i>\n","index":"00248","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> Order. ","index":"00249","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nJohnson:</b> �an ongoing basis. <i>[interjection]</i> ","index":"00250","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> Order. ","index":"00251","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nJohnson:</b> We've said what we've done. We've said what we're going to do. ","index":"00252","speaker":"Derek Johnson"},{"html":"����� I'll\ntell you what we're not going to do, Mr.&nbsp;Deputy Speaker. We're not going\nto stand in this Legislature that represents our democracy and call the members\nof municipalities howling coyotes. That's what we're not going to do. ","index":"00253","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Some\nHonourable Members:</b> Oh, oh. ","index":"00254","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Deputy\nSpeaker:</b> Order. Order. Order. ","index":"00255","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mrs.\nBernadette </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69889089\">Smith</a></b><b>�(Point\nDouglas):</b> The Canadian cancer-care society has withdrawn its sup�port for\nBill&nbsp;56 due to the absence of a consultative process that honours First\nNations' right to self-government. ","index":"00256","speaker":"Bernadette Smith"},{"html":"����� Even\nthough this bill directly impacts Indigenous communities, this government has\ndone no con�sultation with those communities, and Indigenous leaders received\nno advance notice of this bill. This is a clear failure of this government's\nduty to consult and blatant disrespect for First Nations. They deserve better. ","index":"00257","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Will\nthe minister respect Indigenous sovereignty and withdraw Bill&nbsp;56 today? ","index":"00258","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nAudrey </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69889090\">Gordon</a></b><b>�(Minister\nof Mental Health, Wellness and Recovery):</b> I thank the member for the\nquestion. ","index":"00259","speaker":"Audrey Gordon"},{"html":"����� I'm\nnot sure if the House members are aware, but tobacco remains the leading cause\nof preventable death and over 2,000 people perish as a result of smoking every\nyear in this province. ","index":"00260","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Manitoba\nbelieves the health of all residents is important, and we want to ensure that\nwe create spaces across our province for all individuals to be able to benefit\nfrom smoke-free and vapour-free environments. And that is what this bill\nintends to do, Mr. Deputy Speaker: protect the health and well-being of all\nManitobans. ","index":"00261","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> The honourable member for Point Douglas, on a supplementary\nquestion. ","index":"00262","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mrs.\nSmith:</b> The Canadian cancer-care society has said that this bill is\ninconsistent with the requirements of The Path to Reconciliation Act. First\nNations groups have already said that they are considering legal action if this\nbill moves forward. ","index":"00263","speaker":"Andrew Smith"},{"html":"����� Despite\nall of this backlash, this government con�tinues to push through this\nlegislation that isn't really about smoking, it's about control. ","index":"00264","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Will\nthe minister repeal Bill&nbsp;56 and commit to true collaboration with\nIndigenous leaders working forward�moving forward? ","index":"00265","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Ms.\nGordon:</b> Mr. Deputy Speaker, the exclusion of the operation of the\nprovisions in this act to areas under federal jurisdiction is unique in\nManitoba laws. ","index":"00266","speaker":"Audrey Gordon"},{"html":"����� And,\nin fact, we in the Ministry of Mental Health, Wellness and Recovery did a\njurisdictional scan and we asked our counterparts in other provinces, does your\njurisdiction have an exemption on federal lands similar to Manitoba? I want to\ngive you a snapshot of the results: Saskatchewan, no; British Columbia, no;\nAlberta, no; PEI, no; Nova Scotia, no. ","index":"00267","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We are\ngoing to provide Manitobans with the same protection of health and safety, in terms\nof smoke-free and vapour-free environments, as other jurisdictions have done,\nMr. Deputy Speaker. ","index":"00268","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(14:10)","index":"00269","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> The honourable member for Point Douglas, on a final\nsupplementary question. ","index":"00270","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mrs.\nSmith:</b> The minister knows that this bill doesn't do what the minister says\nit does, and the minister also knows that this bill will likely be challenged\nin court.","index":"00271","speaker":"Andrew Smith"},{"html":"����� First\nNations have indicated their willingness to work collaboratively but only\nthrough a fair and consultative process. They oppose the minister's\nheavy-handed approach. It's clear that this bill is just another one of this\ngovernment's attempts to under�mine Indigenous sovereignty.","index":"00272","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Will\nthe minister work within the spirit of recon�ciliation and withdraw Bill 56?","index":"00273","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Ms.\nGordon:</b> In the spirit of reconciliation, we have invited all 63 First\nNations communities to engage with our government on this very important bill. ","index":"00274","speaker":"Audrey Gordon"},{"html":"����� And\nwhile the�our government has jurisdiction to pass laws of general application\nto protect and promote the health of all Manitobans, we certainly respect First\nNations' rights to self-governance. That is why they can choose to pass their\nown bylaws to align with their views on smoking. ","index":"00275","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And we\nwish to engage with First Nations communities to support them in making decisions\nrespecting smoking and vaping in their communities, and we will continue to\nreach out to all First Nations leaders in our province. ","index":"00276","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Tom </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69889092\">Lindsey</a></b><b>�(Flin\nFlon):</b> Today, we learned, through an internal report by the Workers\nCompensation Board, that in the last year they accepted 1,227 COVID‑19\nclaims. That is at least 1,227 confirmed cases of COVID‑19 transmissions\nat Manitoba workplaces. That is at least 1,227 reasons why this government\nneeds to implement a paid sick leave<b> </b>for all Manitoba workers. ","index":"00277","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� Will\nthe minister commit to a provincially supported paid sick leave today?","index":"00278","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nScott </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69889093\">Fielding</a></b><b>�(Minister\nof Finance):</b> There is a paid sick leave program<b>. </b>","index":"00279","speaker":"Scott Fielding"},{"html":"<b>����� </b>That's\nthanks to Premier Pallister and Premier Horgan for�","index":"00280","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> Order. Order. Order. ","index":"00281","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I just\nwant to remind the minister, like, if you're referring to an individual in this\nChamber, it is either the title or their constituency name.","index":"00282","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nFielding:</b> Thanks�that's thanks to our Premier (Mr. Pallister) and the\nPremier of BC, Mr. Deputy Speaker�Mr. Speaker, that led the charge to have sick\nleave�a program with the federal government. The Manitoba government was the\nfirst in the country to pass legislation to make sure that Manitobans, as well\nas Canadians, got the sick leave provisions that are there.","index":"00283","speaker":"Scott Fielding"},{"html":"����� We're\nglad to see the federal government made some changes in terms of length of the\nsick leave program, and that's important to all Manitobans.","index":"00284","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> The honourable member for Flin Flon, on a supplementary\nquestion.","index":"00285","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> What this report shows us is that permanent paid sick days are\nessential for all Manitobans as we move forward through, and hope�fully soon,\nout of this pandemic. While the federal government temporary benefit has been a\nsmall help for many Manitobans during this time, we believe that the province\nshould be a leader in protecting workers, not just now but always.","index":"00286","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� No\nManitoban should have to choose between putting food on their table or\nprotecting public health, whether it's COVID‑19 or the flu.","index":"00287","speaker":""},{"html":"����� So I\nask again: Will the minister commit to a provincial paid sick leave today, yes\nor no?","index":"00288","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nFielding:</b> Well, the member talked about being a leader in this field, and\nour Premier was a leader. In fact, he led the charge to make sure that we did a\nsick leave program.","index":"00289","speaker":"Scott Fielding"},{"html":"����� I can\ntell you, in all the premiers' calls, as well as all the finance ministers'\ncalls, this is a topic that we've pushed for, and we've lobbied effectively to\nmake sure this program's extended. We're happy that we can work with the\nfederal government.","index":"00290","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Again,\nwe are the first in the province of�Canada to pass legislation to ensure people\nhad sick leave pro�visions associated with ours.","index":"00291","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Our\ngovernment has also provided numerous supports. Over 360,000 people got direct\nsupports from this government during the pandemic, Mr.&nbsp;&nbsp;Deputy\nSpeaker.","index":"00292","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> The honourable member for Flin Flon, on a final\nsupplementary question. ","index":"00293","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLindsey:</b> This internal WCB report is only a portion of the workers who got\nsick last year at work. There are likely many Manitobans who are not covered by\nWCB. Teachers and many other Manitobans were not aware that they were eligible\nfor this process.","index":"00294","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� The\nneed for paid sick leave is clear, especially as we heard�head into a third\nwave and after seeing an increase in variants of concern. This is something\nthat we need now and for tomorrow. ","index":"00295","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Will\nthe minister commit to a provincial paid sick leave for all Manitobans for\ntoday, tomorrow and the future, yes or no? ","index":"00296","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nFielding:</b> Our government is taking great pride in supporting Manitobans\nduring the pandemic; over 360,000 Manitobans got some sort of direct support,\nsomewhere up to even $1,500 through the Risk Recognition Program, where over\n80,000 individuals were supported. ","index":"00297","speaker":"Scott Fielding"},{"html":"����� That's\nwhy we pushed. We're going to continue to push at the federal level for\nenhancements, in terms of the sick leave program. We've got a bit of a step of\nthe way there, in terms of enhancement, in terms of the areas, but we're not\ngoing to rest until we can get a further enhanced program at the federal level.\n","index":"00298","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDougald </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69889095\">Lamont</a></b><b>�(St.\nBoniface):</b> Yesterday, I asked the Premier about why front-line essential\nworkers who work with the public, like teachers, people working in education\nand transit workers, are not a vaccine priority for this government. After I&nbsp;&nbsp;asked,\nI received letters from transit workers and teachers who are frustrated because\nthe Province created a free-for-all for vaccinations without ensuring that\nfront-line workers were a priority, because they were so busy working with the\npublic, by the time they could try to book an appointment, there were none\nleft. ","index":"00299","speaker":"Dougald Lamont"},{"html":"����� Is\nthis government going to make sure that people working in education and transit\nworkers, who are at high risk of exposure to COVID, are made a vaccine\npriority? ","index":"00300","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nBrian </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69889096\">Pallister</a></b><b>�(Premier):</b>\nYes, our vaccine team has been markedly successful in getting vaccines out, and\nwe expect with today's announcement, which will assist our international\nworkers in the�essential truck drivers in being able to get vaccinated in North\nDakota on their return to Manitoba, that will be able to assist them. That\nsector needs that support. They've been criticized and harshly treated by some\nalong their routes, and that is not fair or right. But it will also have the\nbeneficial effect of reducing what we hope will be ever-shortening waits for\nothers to get vaccines as well. ","index":"00301","speaker":"Brian Pallister"},{"html":"����� And so\nthat effort will continue, and we will remain focused on it, Mr. Deputy\nSpeaker. ","index":"00302","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> The honourable member for St. Boniface, on a supplemental\nquestion. ","index":"00303","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nLamont:</b> The other group this government is still ignoring are some of the\nmost vulnerable Manitobans: people with underlying conditions of all ages.\nManitobans under 40 who are cancer survivors, people with spina bifida,\ndiabetes or an autoimmune disease, who are at�most at risk of being harmed if\nthey get COVID, are still not a priority for this government. ","index":"00304","speaker":"Dougald Lamont"},{"html":"����� Manitoba\nis the only province that has set age‑40&nbsp;restrictions based on\nbirthdate, not year. I received an email from a woman this morning who has an\nautoimmune disease, but no one will make an exception for her; she has to wait\nuntil her birthday in July to get vaccinated. ","index":"00305","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Is\nthis government going to make sure that people over 18 who are medically\nfragile can get vaccinated now instead of just the free-for-all they've\ncreated? ","index":"00306","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Pallister:</b>\nWell, what the member does again,&nbsp;&nbsp;today, is attempts to discredit\nthe work of not just this government but the vaccine team, the 2,000&nbsp;&nbsp;Manitobans\nthat are working diligently to do a service to all Manitobans. I think that's\ndisrespectful, to put it mildly. ","index":"00307","speaker":"Brian Pallister"},{"html":"����� The\nreal problem is that we have a federal govern�ment that couldn't get vaccines\nto Canadians. So if he wants to speak about vulnerable people, he could talk\nabout Canadians. Canadians as a whole are waiting longer than people all over\nthe world for vaccines. And if the member wants to do something productive, he\ncan support us and support the federal government, because it has taken�has\nendeavoured to undertake to get more domestic production for vaccines in the\nfuture. ","index":"00308","speaker":""},{"html":"����� That\nwould be a positive undertaking and something that we could learn and benefit\nfrom as a consequence of this pandemic rather than dissing the work of\nManitobans. ","index":"00309","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> The honourable member for Tyndall Park, on a final\nsupplementary question. ","index":"00310","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Ms. Cindy\n</b><b><a name=\"_Toc69889098\">Lamoureux</a></b><b>�(Tyndall\nPark):</b> According to the preliminary data from Manitoba's office of the\nChief Medical Examiner,<b> </b>who reported in a CBC article today, which I\ntable, drug overdose deaths in Manitoba surged 87&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent in 2020.\nThis means 372&nbsp;people died of a drug overdose last year here in Manitoba.\nThis is a crisis that must be addressed immediately. ","index":"00311","speaker":"Cindy Lamoureux"},{"html":"����� Now,\nMr. Speaker, I do want to extend our sympathies for all of the families and\nfriends who have lost someone to overdose. ","index":"00312","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And I\nwant to ask this government if they will commit to working with municipalities\nto imme�diately implement supervised consumption sites and offer better\nsupports for those living with addictions. ","index":"00313","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(14:20) ","index":"00314","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nAudrey </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69889099\">Gordon</a></b><b>�(Minister\nof Mental Health, Wellness and Recovery):</b> I want all Manitobans that are\nwatching our session today to know that our government stands beside them\nduring these difficult times, and I sympathize with the loss of every life of\nevery individual in this province and what the families are going through. ","index":"00315","speaker":"Audrey Gordon"},{"html":"����� And\nthat is why our government created this ministry, so we could take a focused\napproach to addressing mental health issues and overdose�the overdose crisis\nthat is affecting our province as well as other provinces across the country.\nAnd we have so many supports available within the health sector and outside the\nhealth sector. I'd be pleased to host a briefing with the member to share all\nthe supports and services that are available. ","index":"00316","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nAndrew </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69889101\">Micklefield</a></b><b>�(Rossmere):</b>\nMr. Speaker, Manitoba is a great province. It's a great province to go to\nuniversity and receive a