aker�<i>[interjection]</i> ","index":"00335","speaker":"Danielle Adams"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> Order. ","index":"00336","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Ms.\nAdams:</b> �I wish to present the following petition to the Legislative\nAssembly. <i>[interjection]</i> ","index":"00337","speaker":"Danielle Adams"},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDeputy Speaker:</b> Order. ","index":"00338","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Ms.\nAdams:</b> The background for this petition is as follows: ","index":"00339","speaker":"Danielle Adams"},{"html":"����� (1)\nThe pandemic has further emphasized the need for quality, affordable,\naccessible child care and has demonstrated the government has failed to ensure\nchild care is accessible to all Manitoba families. ","index":"00340","speaker":""},{"html":"����� �(2)\nOver 90&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent of Manitoba children receive child care through a\nnon-profit, licensed centre, and yet funding has been frozen since 2016. These\ncuts have resulted in many early childhood educators leaving the sector. ","index":"00341","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (3)\nWhile child-care centres have faced increased costs associated with the loss of\nparent fees due to the COVID‑19 closures and have spent thousands on PPE,\nwhen open, to keep kids safe, the provincial govern�ment has provided no\nadditional funding or supports. ","index":"00342","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (4)\nThe government spent less than 1&nbsp;per&nbsp;cent of the $18‑million\ntemporary child-care grant and instead gave KPMG double their contract, nearly\n$600,000, to conduct a review that will raise parent fees and lay the\ngroundwork for privatization. ","index":"00343","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (5)\nThe provincial government's cuts to the �nursery school grant is doubling\nparent fees for hundreds of families, making child care less afford�able and\naccessible. ","index":"00344","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (6)\nThe provincial government passed bill 34, the budget implementation and status\namendment act, which removes the cap on child-care fees for private sector\nbusinesses. ","index":"00345","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We\npetition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows: ","index":"00346","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To\nurge the provincial government to reverse changes to the nursery school grants\nand to end the freeze on child-care operating grants while com�mitting to\nkeeping child care public, affordable, accessible for all Manitobans. ","index":"00347","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\npetition is signed by many Manitobans. ","index":"00348","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Deputy\nSpeaker:</b> In accordance to rule&nbsp;133-6, when petitions are read they are\ndeemed to be received by the House. ","index":"00349","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Jon </b><b><a name=\"_Toc69889110\">Gerrard</a></b><b>�(River\nHeights): </b>Mr. Deputy Speaker, I wish to present the following petition to\nthe Legislative Assembly. ","index":"00350","speaker":"Jon Gerrard"},{"html":"����� The background to this petition is as follows: ","index":"00351","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The Vivian sands project is a proposed silica sand mine and\nprocessing plant to be built in the RM of Springfield. The overall project\nincludes mining claims of over 85,000 hectares, making it the largest claim\never given to a single company in Manitoba's history. It is larger than the\ncity of Winnipeg, which is 46,410 hectares. ","index":"00352","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The amount of dry, solid sand mined, produced per year according to\nthe EAP is 1.36&nbsp;million tons, and much of this sand will be used in\nfracking. ","index":"00353","speaker":""},{"html":"����� A major concern of the proposed mine and plant&nbsp;&nbsp;is that,\nif developed, it could contaminate the&nbsp;Sandilands aquifer, including both\ncarbonate and sandstone aquifers, which covers much of south�eastern Manitoba.\nIt has excellent water quality and is the water source for tens of thousands of\nManitobans, including many municipal water systems, agriculture, industry,\nprivate wells and abundance of wildlife and ecosystems. Further, people in the\nIndigenous com�munities that are potentially affected by this were not afforded\nthe required Indigenous consultation from either federal or provincial\ngovernment officials. ","index":"00354","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The sustainable yield of the combined sandstone and carbonate\naquifers has still not yet been established by provincial authorities.","index":"00355","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The mine could cause leaching of acid and heavy metals and pollute\nthe aquifer, as it will go down 200&nbsp;feet into the Winnipeg formation of\nthe sandstone aquifer. There is concern that the shale, which separates the\ncarbonate and sandstone aquifers�sand and pyritic oolite itself contains\nsulphides�will, when exposed to injected air from the CanWhite Sands extraction\nprocess, turn to acid. ","index":"00356","speaker":""},{"html":"����� An\nadditional concern with the proposed mine and plant is the potential to pollute\nthe Brokenhead River and the aquatic food chain leading to Lake Winnipeg. ","index":"00357","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Residents\nin the area have also expressed fears of being overexposed to silica dust\nduring production, as there has been a demonstrated lack of safety and environmental\nprocedures by the CanWhite Sands Corporation during the exploratory drilling\nphase. Signage and fencing has been poor; identifying and required mine claim\ntags were missing; there were no warnings for silica dust exposure and no\ncoverings to prevent exposure of the silica stockpiles to the elements. ","index":"00358","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(14:30)","index":"00359","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Residents' concerns include the fact that boreholes, which\nshould've been promptly and proper��ly sealed, were left open for a year. The\ndrilling of hundreds of improperly sealed boreholes yearly create significant\nrisks of surface contamination, mixing of aquifer waters and drainage of\nsurface fecal matters into the aquifer.","index":"00360","speaker":""},{"html":"����� There is also a risk of subsidence around each borehole as a result\nof sand extraction.","index":"00361","speaker":""},{"html":"����� There are also potential transboundary issues that need to be\naddressed as the aquifers extend into Minnesota. ","index":"00362","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This project should not proceed, as no licensing conditions and\nmitigation measures will alleviate the risk to all Manitobans and the environment\nsince CanWhite Sands Corporation plans to use an unprecedented mining technique\nwith no established safe outcome. The corporation has gone on record indicating\nthat it does not know how to mine for the silica in the water supply and need\nto develop a new extraction methodology that has never been done before.","index":"00363","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Contamination of the aquifer and the environment is irreversible\nand there are many surface sources of high purity silica that can be extracted\nwithout endangering two essential regional aquifers. ","index":"00364","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00365","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the provincial government to undertake a combined review of\nthe Vivian Sand Facility processing plant and the mining/extraction portion of\nthe operation as a class 3 development with a review by Manitoba's Clean\nEnvironment Commission to include public hearings and participant funding.","index":"00366","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the provincial government to halt all activity at the mine\nand plant until the Clean Environment Commission's review is completed and the\nproject proposal has been thoroughly evaluated.","index":"00367","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Signed by James Shurnell <i>[phonetic]</i>, Gavin Barkman, M. Herd\nand many, many others. ","index":